#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:146
msgid "Extended attribute (xattr) mapping"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:148
msgid ""
"By default the name of xattr's used by the client are passed through to the "
"server file system.  This can be a problem where either those xattr names "
"are used by something on the server (e.g. selinux client/server confusion) "
"or if the ``virtiofsd`` is running in a container with restricted privileges "
"where it cannot access some attributes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:155
msgid "Mapping syntax"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:157
msgid ""
"A mapping of xattr names can be made using -o xattrmap=mapping where the "
"``mapping`` string consists of a series of rules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:160
msgid ""
"The first matching rule terminates the mapping. The set of rules must "
"include a terminating rule to match any remaining attributes at the end."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:164
msgid ""
"Each rule consists of a number of fields separated with a separator that is "
"the first non-white space character in the rule.  This separator must then "
"be used for the whole rule. White space may be added before and after each "
"rule."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:169
msgid "Using ':' as the separator a rule is of the form:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:171
msgid "``:type:scope:key:prepend:``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:173
msgid "**scope** is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:175
msgid "'client' - match 'key' against a xattr name from the client for"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:176
msgid "setxattr/getxattr/removexattr"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:177
msgid "'server' - match 'prepend' against a xattr name from the server"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:178
msgid "for listxattr"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:179
msgid "'all' - can be used to make a single rule where both the server"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:180
msgid "and client matches are triggered."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:182
msgid "**type** is one of:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:184
msgid ""
"'prefix' - is designed to prepend and strip a prefix;  the modified "
"attributes then being passed on to the client/server."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:187
msgid ""
"'ok' - Causes the rule set to be terminated when a match is found while "
"allowing matching xattr's through unchanged. It is intended both as a way of "
"explicitly terminating the list of rules, and to allow some xattr's to skip "
"following rules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:192
msgid ""
"'bad' - If a client tries to use a name matching 'key' it's denied using "
"EPERM; when the server passes an attribute name matching 'prepend' it's "
"hidden.  In many ways it's use is very like 'ok' as either an explicit "
"terminator or for special handling of certain patterns."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:198
msgid ""
"'unsupported' - If a client tries to use a name matching 'key' it's denied "
"using ENOTSUP; when the server passes an attribute name matching 'prepend' "
"it's hidden.  In many ways it's use is very like 'ok' as either an explicit "
"terminator or for special handling of certain patterns."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:204
msgid ""
"**key** is a string tested as a prefix on an attribute name originating on "
"the client.  It maybe empty in which case a 'client' rule will always match "
"on client names."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:208
msgid ""
"**prepend** is a string tested as a prefix on an attribute name originating "
"on the server, and used as a new prefix.  It may be empty in which case a "
"'server' rule will always match on all names from the server."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:213
msgid "e.g.:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:215
msgid "``:prefix:client:trusted.:user.virtiofs.:``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:217
msgid ""
"will match 'trusted.' attributes in client calls and prefix them before "
"passing them to the server."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:220
msgid "``:prefix:server::user.virtiofs.:``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:222
msgid "will strip 'user.virtiofs.' from all server replies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:224
msgid "``:prefix:all:trusted.:user.virtiofs.:``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:226
msgid "combines the previous two cases into a single rule."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:228
msgid "``:ok:client:user.::``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:230
msgid ""
"will allow get/set xattr for 'user.' xattr's and ignore following rules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:233
msgid "``:ok:server::security.:``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:235
msgid ""
"will pass 'securty.' xattr's in listxattr from the server and ignore "
"following rules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:238
msgid "``:ok:all:::``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:240
msgid ""
"will terminate the rule search passing any remaining attributes in both "
"directions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:243
msgid "``:bad:server::security.:``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:245
msgid "would hide 'security.' xattr's in listxattr from the server."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:247
msgid "A simpler 'map' type provides a shorter syntax for the common case:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:249
msgid "``:map:key:prepend:``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:251
msgid ""
"The 'map' type adds a number of separate rules to add **prepend** as a "
"prefix to the matched **key** (or all attributes if **key** is empty). There "
"may be at most one 'map' rule and it must be the last rule in the set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:255
msgid ""
"Note: When the 'security.capability' xattr is remapped, the daemon has to do "
"extra work to remove it during many operations, which the host kernel "
"normally does itself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:260
msgid "Security considerations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:262
msgid ""
"Operating systems typically partition the xattr namespace using well defined "
"name prefixes. Each partition may have different access controls applied. "
"For example, on Linux there are multiple partitions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:267
msgid "``system.*`` - access varies depending on attribute & filesystem"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:268
msgid "``security.*`` - only processes with CAP_SYS_ADMIN"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:269
msgid "``trusted.*`` - only processes with CAP_SYS_ADMIN"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:270
msgid "``user.*`` - any process granted by file permissions / ownership"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:272
msgid ""
"While other OS such as FreeBSD have different name prefixes and access "
"control rules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:275
msgid ""
"When remapping attributes on the host, it is important to ensure that the "
"remapping does not allow a guest user to evade the guest access control "
"rules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:279
msgid ""
"Consider if ``trusted.*`` from the guest was remapped to ``user.virtiofs."
"trusted*`` in the host. An unprivileged user in a Linux guest has the "
"ability to write to xattrs under ``user.*``. Thus the user can evade the "
"access control restriction on ``trusted.*`` by instead writing to ``user."
"virtiofs.trusted.*``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:286
msgid ""
"As noted above, the partitions used and access controls applied, will vary "
"across guest OS, so it is not wise to try to predict what the guest OS will "
"use."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:290
msgid ""
"The simplest way to avoid an insecure configuration is to remap all xattrs "
"at once, to a given fixed prefix. This is shown in example (1) below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:294
msgid ""
"If selectively mapping only a subset of xattr prefixes, then rules must be "
"added to explicitly block direct access to the target of the remapping. This "
"is shown in example (2) below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:300
msgid "Mapping examples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:302
msgid "Prefix all attributes with 'user.virtiofs.'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:306
msgid "-o xattrmap=\":prefix:all::user.virtiofs.::bad:all:::\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:309
msgid ""
"This uses two rules, using : as the field separator; the first rule prefixes "
"and strips 'user.virtiofs.', the second rule hides any non-prefixed "
"attributes that the host set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:314 ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:344
msgid "This is equivalent to the 'map' rule:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:318
msgid "-o xattrmap=\":map::user.virtiofs.:\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:320
msgid "Prefix 'trusted.' attributes, allow others through"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:324
msgid ""
"\"/prefix/all/trusted./user.virtiofs./\n"
" /bad/server//trusted./\n"
" /bad/client/user.virtiofs.//\n"
" /ok/all///\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:330
msgid ""
"Here there are four rules, using / as the field separator, and also "
"demonstrating that new lines can be included between rules. The first rule "
"is the prefixing of 'trusted.' and stripping of 'user.virtiofs.'. The second "
"rule hides unprefixed 'trusted.' attributes on the host. The third rule "
"stops a guest from explicitly setting the 'user.virtiofs.' path directly to "
"prevent access control bypass on the target of the earlier prefix remapping. "
"Finally, the fourth rule lets all remaining attributes through."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:348
msgid "-o xattrmap=\"/map/trusted./user.virtiofs./\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:350
msgid "Hide 'security.' attributes, and allow everything else"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:354
msgid ""
"\"/bad/all/security./security./\n"
" /ok/all///'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:357
msgid ""
"The first rule combines what could be separate client and server rules into "
"a single 'all' rule, matching 'security.' in either client arguments or "
"lists returned from the host.  This stops the client seeing any 'security.' "
"attributes on the server and stops it setting any."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:364
msgid "SELinux support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:365
msgid ""
"One can enable support for SELinux by running virtiofsd with option \"-o "
"security_label\". But this will try to save guest's security context in "
"xattr security.selinux on host and it might fail if host's SELinux policy "
"does not permit virtiofsd to do this operation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:370
msgid ""
"Hence, it is preferred to remap guest's \"security.selinux\" xattr to say "
"\"trusted.virtiofs.security.selinux\" on host."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:373
msgid "\"-o xattrmap=:map:security.selinux:trusted.virtiofs.:\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:375
msgid ""
"This will make sure that guest and host's SELinux xattrs on same file remain "
"separate and not interfere with each other. And will allow both host and "
"guest to implement their own separate SELinux policies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:379
msgid ""
"Setting trusted xattr on host requires CAP_SYS_ADMIN. So one will need add "
"this capability to daemon."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:382
msgid "\"-o modcaps=+sys_admin\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tools/virtiofsd.rst:384
msgid ""
"Giving CAP_SYS_ADMIN increases the risk on system. Now virtiofsd is more "
"powerful and if gets compromised, it can do lot of damage to host system. So "
"keep this trade-off in my mind while making a decision."
msgstr ""

